[[en:Yūsoku Kojitsu]]
[[sn:Yūsoku Kojitsu]]
[[ja:有職故実]]

{{Refimprove|date=July 2023}}

'''Yūsoku Kojitsu''' (有職故実) refers to the study and traditions of ancient customs, regulations, systems, etiquette, ceremonies, attire, and practices of the {{ill|Imperial Court|ja|朝廷 (日本)|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|samurai class|ja|武家|12=draft|12=draft}}. The term also encompasses the study of these traditions.

== Overview ==

"Yūsoku" denotes knowledge of past precedents, while "kojitsu" refers to persuasive grounds or norms regarding public and private conduct. Individuals well-versed in these areas were referred to as '''yūsokusha''' (有職者), a term later shortened to "yūsoku."

== Pre-Edo Period ==

=== Court Traditions ===

From the mid-{{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the systematization of precedents advanced under the regency of {{ill|Fujiwara no Tadahira|ja|藤原忠平|12=draft|12=draft}}, who established the basic forms of court rituals. These rituals were rationalized using the knowledge of Tadahira’s father, {{ill|Fujiwara no Mototsune|ja|藤原基経|12=draft|12=draft}}, and his elder brother, {{ill|Fujiwara no Tokihira|ja|藤原時平|12=draft|12=draft}}, along with imperial orders and references to {{ill|Geki diaries|ja|外記日記|12=draft|12=draft}}. This tradition was orally transmitted to his sons, forming two major schools of court ritual: the {{ill|Ono no Miya school|ja|小野宮流|12=draft|12=draft}} of his elder son, {{ill|Fujiwara no Saneyori|ja|藤原実頼|12=draft|12=draft}}, and the {{ill|Kujo school|ja|九条流|12=draft|12=draft}} of his younger son, {{ill|Fujiwara no Morosuke|ja|藤原師輔|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{ill|Otsu Toru|ja|大津透|12=draft|12=draft}}, ''Michinaga and the Court Society: Japanese History 06'', Kodansha Academic Library, ISBN 978-4062689069.</ref> Other schools, such as the {{ill|Koitijo school|ja|小一条流|12=draft|12=draft}} of Morosuke’s fifth son and the later {{ill|Mido school|ja|御堂流|12=draft|12=draft}}, also emerged.

During the {{ill|Cloistered rule|ja|院政|Cloistered rule=Cloistered rule|lt=insei|12=draft|12=draft}} period, the {{ill|Tsuchimikado school|ja|土御門流|12=draft|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Hanazono school|ja|花園流|12=draft|12=draft}} were formed, the latter completed by figures such as {{ill|Tokudaiji Sanetsune|ja|徳大寺実定|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Sanjō Sanefusa|ja|三条実房|12=draft|12=draft}}. In the late Heian period, {{ill|Matsudono Motofusa|ja|松殿基房|12=draft|12=draft}} synthesized many traditions into what became known as the "Matsudono Kanpaku Theory," which influenced court society for centuries.

As {{ill|kanji-uke|ja|官司請負制|12=draft|12=draft}} became widespread, some families such as the {{ill|Tokudaiji family|ja|徳大寺家|12=draft|12=draft}} (Kujo school) and the {{ill|Ōi no Mikado family|ja|大炊御門家|12=draft|12=draft}} (Mido school) adopted yūsoku kojitsu as their professional legacy.

=== Bushi Traditions ===

In the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|12=draft|12=draft}} emphasized bushi traditions. Over time, practices from Kyoto and local customs blended to form the foundations of samurai etiquette. Schools like the {{ill|Ogasawara school|ja|小笠原流|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Ise school|ja|伊勢流|12=draft|12=draft}} emerged during the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Edo Period ==

During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, independent researchers such as {{ill|Tsuboi Yoshitomo|ja|壺井義知|12=draft|12=draft}} gained recognition. Influential figures from the {{ill|Imperial Court|ja|公家|1=Kuge|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|samurai class|ja|武家|12=draft|12=draft}} further elevated the academic level of these studies. Samurai experts like {{ill|Ise Sadatake|ja|伊勢貞丈|12=draft|12=draft}} contributed to many texts, while court nobles such as {{ill|Hiramatsu Tokikata|ja|平松時方|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Uramatsu Kōyo|ja|裏松光世|12=draft|12=draft}} advanced public and private yūsoku traditions.

== Modern Period ==

With the abolition of traditional court and samurai systems in the modern period, yūsoku kojitsu lost its practical significance. However, it continued to be studied as part of {{ill|historical studies|ja|歴史学|12=draft|12=draft}} or Japanese literary studies, with contributions from scholars like {{ill|Sato Makoto|ja|佐藤誠実|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Wada Hidematsu|ja|和田英松|12=draft|12=draft}}.

