In the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|12=draft|12=draft}} emphasized bushi traditions. Over time, practices from Kyoto and local customs blended to form the foundations of samurai etiquette. Schools like the {{ill|Ogasawara school|ja|小笠原流|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Ise school|ja|伊勢流|12=draft|12=draft}} emerged during the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Edo Period ==

During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, independent researchers such as {{ill|Tsuboi Yoshitomo|ja|壺井義知|12=draft|12=draft}} gained recognition. Influential figures from the {{ill|Imperial Court|ja|公家|1=Kuge|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|samurai class|ja|武家|12=draft|12=draft}} further elevated the academic level of these studies. Samurai experts like {{ill|Ise Sadatake|ja|伊勢貞丈|12=draft|12=draft}} contributed to many texts, while court nobles such as {{ill|Hiramatsu Tokikata|ja|平松時方|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Uramatsu Kōyo|ja|裏松光世|12=draft|12=draft}} advanced public and private yūsoku traditions.

== Modern Period ==

With the abolition of traditional court and samurai systems in the modern period, yūsoku kojitsu lost its practical significance. However, it continued to be studied as part of {{ill|historical studies|ja|歴史学|12=draft|12=draft}} or Japanese literary studies, with contributions from scholars like {{ill|Sato Makoto|ja|佐藤誠実|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Wada Hidematsu|ja|和田英松|12=draft|12=draft}}.

