[[en:Yūsoku Kojitsu]]
[[sn:Yūsoku Kojitsu]]
[[ja:有職故実]]

{{Refimprove|date=July 2023}}

'''Yūsoku Kojitsu''' (有職故実) refers to the study and traditions of ancient customs, regulations, systems, etiquette, ceremonies, attire, and practices of the {{ill|Imperial Court|ja|朝廷 (日本)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Court|qq=}} and {{ill|samurai class|ja|武家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/samurai class|qq=}}. The term also encompasses the study of these traditions.

== Overview ==

"Yūsoku" denotes knowledge of past precedents, while "kojitsu" refers to persuasive grounds or norms regarding public and private conduct. Individuals well-versed in these areas were referred to as '''yūsokusha''' (有職者), a term later shortened to "yūsoku."

== Pre-Edo Period ==

=== Court Traditions ===

From the mid-{{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heian period|qq=}}, the systematization of precedents advanced under the regency of {{ill|Fujiwara no Tadahira|ja|藤原忠平|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Tadahira|qq=}}, who established the basic forms of court rituals. These rituals were rationalized using the knowledge of Tadahira’s father, {{ill|Fujiwara no Mototsune|ja|藤原基経|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Mototsune|qq=}}, and his elder brother, {{ill|Fujiwara no Tokihira|ja|藤原時平|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Tokihira|qq=}}, along with imperial orders and references to {{ill|Geki diaries|ja|外記日記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Geki diaries|qq=}}. This tradition was orally transmitted to his sons, forming two major schools of court ritual: the {{ill|Ono no Miya school|ja|小野宮流|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ono no Miya school|qq=}} of his elder son, {{ill|Fujiwara no Saneyori|ja|藤原実頼|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Saneyori|qq=}}, and the {{ill|Kujo school|ja|九条流|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujo school|qq=}} of his younger son, {{ill|Fujiwara no Morosuke|ja|藤原師輔|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Morosuke|qq=}}.<ref>{{ill|Otsu Toru|ja|大津透|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Otsu Toru|qq=}}, ''Michinaga and the Court Society: Japanese History 06'', Kodansha Academic Library, ISBN 978-4062689069.</ref> Other schools, such as the {{ill|Koitijo school|ja|小一条流|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Koitijo school|qq=}} of Morosuke’s fifth son and the later {{ill|Mido school|ja|御堂流|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mido school|qq=}}, also emerged.

During the {{ill|Cloistered rule|ja|院政|Cloistered rule=Cloistered rule|lt=insei|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cloistered rule|qq=}} period, the {{ill|Tsuchimikado school|ja|土御門流|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado school|qq=}} and the {{ill|Hanazono school|ja|花園流|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hanazono school|qq=}} were formed, the latter completed by figures such as {{ill|Tokudaiji Sanetsune|ja|徳大寺実定|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokudaiji Sanetsune|qq=}} and {{ill|Sanjō Sanefusa|ja|三条実房|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sanjō Sanefusa|qq=}}. In the late Heian period, {{ill|Matsudono Motofusa|ja|松殿基房|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsudono Motofusa|qq=}} synthesized many traditions into what became known as the "Matsudono Kanpaku Theory," which influenced court society for centuries.

As {{ill|kanji-uke|ja|官司請負制|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kanji-uke|qq=}} became widespread, some families such as the {{ill|Tokudaiji family|ja|徳大寺家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokudaiji family|qq=}} (Kujo school) and the {{ill|Ōi no Mikado family|ja|大炊御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōi no Mikado family|qq=}} (Mido school) adopted yūsoku kojitsu as their professional legacy.

=== Bushi Traditions ===

In the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura period|qq=}}, {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoritomo|qq=}} emphasized bushi traditions. Over time, practices from Kyoto and local customs blended to form the foundations of samurai etiquette. Schools like the {{ill|Ogasawara school|ja|小笠原流|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ogasawara school|qq=}} and {{ill|Ise school|ja|伊勢流|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise school|qq=}} emerged during the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muromachi period|qq=}}.

== Edo Period ==

During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}, independent researchers such as {{ill|Tsuboi Yoshitomo|ja|壺井義知|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuboi Yoshitomo|qq=}} gained recognition. Influential figures from the {{ill|Imperial Court|ja|公家|1=Kuge|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Court|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuge|qq=}} and {{ill|samurai class|ja|武家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/samurai class|qq=}} further elevated the academic level of these studies. Samurai experts like {{ill|Ise Sadatake|ja|伊勢貞丈|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Sadatake|qq=}} contributed to many texts, while court nobles such as {{ill|Hiramatsu Tokikata|ja|平松時方|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiramatsu Tokikata|qq=}} and {{ill|Uramatsu Kōyo|ja|裏松光世|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Uramatsu Kōyo|qq=}} advanced public and private yūsoku traditions.

== Modern Period ==

With the abolition of traditional court and samurai systems in the modern period, yūsoku kojitsu lost its practical significance. However, it continued to be studied as part of {{ill|historical studies|ja|歴史学|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/historical studies|qq=}} or Japanese literary studies, with contributions from scholars like {{ill|Sato Makoto|ja|佐藤誠実|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sato Makoto|qq=}} and {{ill|Wada Hidematsu|ja|和田英松|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wada Hidematsu|qq=}}.

